08145nam a22009855i 9780812207989DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20132013pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979910469  a97808122079897 a10.9783/97808122079892doi  a(DE-B1597)449693  a(OCoLC)859161000  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aPOL0090002bisacsh04a320.9008900aPower Sharing in Deeply Divided Places /ced. by Brendan O'Leary, Joanne McEvoy. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (448 p.) :b25 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNational and Ethnic Conflict in the 21st Century00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tCHAPTER 1. Power Sharing in Deeply Divided Places: An Advocate’s Introduction -- tPART I. Power Sharing and Electoral Systems -- tCHAPTER 2. Electoral Rules and Ethnic Representation and Accommodation: Combining Social Choice and Electoral System Perspectives -- tCHAPTER 3. The Track Record of Centripetalism in Deeply Divided Places -- tCHAPTER 4. Electoral Engineering for a Stalled Federation -- tPART II. Historical and Conceptual Forays into Power Sharing -- tCHAPTER 5. A Theory of Accommodation Versus Conflict: With Special Reference to the Israel- Palestine Conflict -- tCHAPTER 6. The Success of Religion as a Source for Compromise in Divided Empires: Ottoman and Safavid, Past and Present -- tCHAPTER 7. Geopolitics and the Long- Term Construction of Democracy -- tCHAPTER 8. Courts, Constitutions, and the Limits of Majoritarianism -- tPART III. Contemporary Power- Sharing Questions -- tCHAPTER 9. A Revised Theory of Federacy and a Case Study of Civil War Termination in Aceh, Indonesia -- tCHAPTER 10. We Forbid! The Mutual Veto and Power- Sharing Democracy -- tCHAPTER 11. Northern Ireland: Power Sharing, Contact, Identity, and Leadership -- tCHAPTER 12. Public Opinion and Power Sharing in Deeply Divided Places -- tCHAPTER 13. The Balkans: The Promotion of Power Sharing by Outsiders -- tCHAPTER 14. Governing Polarized Cities -- tCHAPTER 15. Power Sharing in Kirkuk: The Need for Compromise -- tCHAPTER 16. Power Sharing: An Advocate’s Conclusion -- tContributors -- tIndex -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPower sharing may be broadly defined as any set of arrangements that prevents one political agency or collective from monopolizing power, whether temporarily or permanently. Ideally, such measures promote inclusiveness or at least the coexistence of divergent cultures within a state. In places deeply divided by national, ethnic, linguistic, or religious conflict, power sharing is the standard prescription for reconciling antagonistic groups, particularly where genocide, expulsion, or coerced assimilation threaten the lives and rights of minority peoples. In recent history, the success record of this measure is mixed.Power Sharing in Deeply Divided Places features fifteen analytical studies of power-sharing systems, past and present, as well as critical evaluations of the role of electoral systems and courts in their implementation. Interdisciplinary and international in formation and execution, the chapters encompass divided cities such as Belfast, Jerusalem, Kirkuk, and Sarajevo and divided places such as Belgium, Israel/Palestine, Northern Ireland, and South Africa, as well as the Holy Roman Empire, the Saffavid Empire, Aceh in Indonesia, and the European Union.Equally suitable for specialists, teachers, and students, Power Sharing in Deeply Divided Places considers the merits and defects of an array of variant systems and provides explanations of their emergence, maintenance, and failings; some essays offer lucid proposals targeted at particular places. While this volume does not presume that power sharing is a panacea for social reconciliation, it does suggest how it can help foster peace and democracy in conflict-torn countries.Contributors: Liam Anderson, Florian Bieber, Scott A. Bollens, Benjamin Braude, Ed Cairns, Randall Collins, Kris Deschouwer, Bernard Grofman, Colin Irwin, Samuel Issacharoff, Allison McCulloch, Joanne McEvoy, Brendan O'Leary, Philippe van Parijs, Alfred Stepan, Ronald Wintrobe.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 4aHuman Rights. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Comparative Politics.2bisacsh  aHuman Rights.  aLaw.  aPolitical Science.  aPublic Policy.1 aAnderson, Liam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBieber, Florian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBollens, Scott A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBraude, Benjamin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCairns, Ed, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCollins, Randall, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeschouwer, Kris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrofman, Bernard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIrwin, Colin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIssacharoff, Samuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcCulloch, Allison, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcEvoy, Joanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcEvoy, Joanne, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aO'Leary, Brendan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aO’Leary, Brendan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStepan, Alfred, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 